{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514099"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.09,0.1,0.17,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4794"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man presents to his general practitioner for a regular review of his hypertension. He was diagnosed with hypertension 30 years ago, and it has always been poorly controlled despite the commencement of antihypertensives. On further history, he reports worsening shortness of breath for the past two months, which is exacerbated by lying down. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly short of breath. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 150/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination is unremarkable. Respiratory examination reveals fine bilateral basal crackles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ECG changes is the most likely finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flat T waves in leads V4-V6, and PR interval of 200 ms","Presence of U waves in the precordial leads (V1-V6)","PR interval of 200 ms and QRS duration of 110 ms","Negative QRS complex and dominant S wave in lead  I and positive QRS complex in aVF","Increased R wave amplitude in V5-V6 and deep S wave in V1-V2"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) with symptoms of heart failure is the most likely diagnosis. Whilst ECG is useful to risk stratify the patient\u0027s symptoms, there is poor sensitivity and an echocardiogram would be essential for the diagnostic work-up of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased R wave amplitude in V5-V6 and deep S wave in V1-V2: \u003C/strong\u003EThis demonstrates the Sokolow-Lyon voltage criteria for LVH in which S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 is \u0026gt; 35 mm and is accompanied by a non-voltage criterion (increased R wave peak time \u0026gt; 50 ms in leads V5 or V6). This finding would be of most concern in this case, as LVH is a common complication of long-standing hypertension and may contribute to the patient\u0027s worsening shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlat T waves in leads V4-V6 and PR interval of 200 ms:\u003C/strong\u003E Flat T waves can be a normal finding in some individuals, particularly in the precordial leads. They may also be seen in cases of electrolyte imbalances, ischemia, or other non-specific causes. While flat T waves may warrant further investigation, they are not as concerning as the potential LVH in this patient with long-standing hypertension. A PR interval of 210 ms is at the upper limit of the normal range but is still considered a normal finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of U waves in the precordial leads (V1, V2, V3, V4, V5, and V6) and a QRS duration of 120 ms: \u003C/strong\u003EU waves are small positive deflections that follow the T wave on an ECG. They are usually seen in leads V2-V3 and sometimes in leads V4-V6. U waves can be a normal variant, particularly in cases of slow heart rates. The other main cause of prominent U waves is severe hypokalaemia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPR interval length of 200 ms and QRS duration of 110 ms:\u003C/strong\u003E A PR interval of 200 ms is at the upper limit of the normal range (120-200 ms) but is still considered a normal finding. The PR interval represents the time it takes for electrical impulses to travel from the sinoatrial (SA) node to the atrioventricular (AV) node. A QRS duration of 110 ms is within the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegative QRS complex and dominant S wave in lead I and positive QRS complex in aVF: \u003C/strong\u003EThis indicates right axis deviation refers to an electrical axis shift to the right, typically seen in leads I and aVF. Right axis deviation can be a normal finding in tall, thin individuals or during pregnancy. It can also be seen in conditions such as right ventricular hypertrophy, pulmonary disease, or lateral myocardial infarction. However, in this patient with a history of poorly controlled hypertension, changes consistent with LVH is a more likely finding than right axis deviation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["To diagnose left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH), there must be one voltage criterion + one non-voltage criterion","The most common cause of left ventricular hypertrophy is hypertension"],"references":["Burns E, Buttner R. Left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) [Internet]. 2021 [cited 2023 Aug 5]. Available from: https://litfl.com/left-ventricular-hypertrophy-lvh-ecg-library/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T16:34:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T16:35:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emo